article.headline: UMBC 45, New Hampshire 44
article.story: CATONSVILLE, Md. (AP) -- Chris Pugh hit a 3-pointer from the left wing with 2.2 seconds left, lifting Maryland-Baltimore County over New Hampshire 45-44 Thursday night. Mike Housman scored 12 points for the Retrievers (8-13, 4-4 America East), who snapped New Hampshire's three-game winning streak. Tom Young grabbed 10 rebounds. Blagoj Janev led the Wildcats (8-13, 4-4) with 17 points. Radar Onguetou added 11 points and 10 rebounds, and Tyrece Gibbs scored 11 points. UMBC, which had lost four of five games, used a 12-2 run midway through the second half to erase a 10-point New Hampshire lead. Pugh's four-point play put the Retrievers ahead 39-36 with 8:45 to go. But Janev's baseline layup gave the Wildcats a 40-30 lead with 7:40 left. A pair of free throws by Onguetou with 3:57 remaining made it 44-42. UMBC ended up with the ball following a wild tipped-ball scrum after Jermaine Anderson missed a foul shot with 24.1 seconds left. After a Retriever timeout, Pugh inbounded the ball to Jay Greene with 10 seconds left. Greene wanted to pass to Brian Hodges, who was double-teamed on the right wing, but found Pugh was open on the left side for the game-winner. New Hampshire led 23-14 at halftime, as the Retrievers matched their lowest output for a half this season. Neither team shot well, the Wildcats connecting on seven of 30 attempts from the floor in the opening 20 minutes, while UMBC was 7-for-25 and endured a 14:40 scoreless span.
